## 1. Reflecting on Coding in Markdown
**Situation:** As I moved into my third year of Information Technology, I realized that a standard document wasn't enough to
showcase my skills. I needed a professional digital portfolio that looked the part and demonstrated my technical capabilities through its own construction.
**Goal:** My objective was to use GitHub Flavored Markdown (GFM) to build a structured CV and detailed project descriptions.
I wanted to move beyond basic text and use industry-standard documentation tools to show that I can communicate effectively within a developer’s workflow.
**Action:** Working through Git Bash to manage my local repository, I drafted the CV using Markdown syntax.
I utilized headers for clear organization and tables to display my technical skills. To make the project descriptions more dynamic,
I applied GFM features like task lists to track milestones and ensured all code snippets featured clean, accurate syntax highlighting.
**Outcome:** The result was a polished, professional CV that is natively readable and well-organized on GitHub.
This process significantly improved my proficiency in Markdown— a skill I now recognize as vital for producing high-quality project documentation in the software industry.

